1. Rational & irrational numbers


ID is: 1803 Seed is: 8217

Special sets: identifying rational numbers

Is the following statement true or false: −4∈Q−4∈Q?

Answer: The statement is .
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

The set of rational numbers includes any number which can be written as a fraction of two integers. This includes all integers, any decimal number which terminates, and any decimal number which has a repeating pattern.

STEP: <no title>
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

The set of rational numbers includes all numbers which can be written as a fraction of two integers, as long as the denominator is not zero. The definition looks like this: Q={ab:a,b∈Z,b≠0}Q={ab:a,b∈Z,b≠0}. Here is a summary of what this means:

  • the set of rational numbers includes:
    1. all fractions with integers in the numerator and denominator, as long as the denominator is not zero, for example: 12;−711;2005012;−711;20050
    2. all integers because integers can be written as fractions, for example 5=515=51
    3. all terminating decimal numbers, for example: 4,2;−1,5;3,509274654,2;−1,5;3,50927465
    4. all decimal numbers with a recurring pattern, for example: 0,3333…;2,˙6;6,5827827827…0,3333…;2,6˙;6,5827827827…
  • the set of rational numbers does not include:
    1. any fraction where the denominator is zero
    2. decimal numbers which go on forever without a repeating pattern, for example: 2,4681012…;3,14159265…2,4681012…;3,14159265…

In this question the number we must decide if −4−4 is an element of the rational numbers. −4−4 is an integer, and it is a rational number because is can be written as a fraction: −4=−41−4=−41.

The statement −4∈Q−4∈Q is True.

Rational and irrational numbers

Is the following number rational, irrational or neither?

π0π0

Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

If you can simplify the number, start by doing that. Then you must decide if the number can also be written as a fraction of two integers. If it can, then it is a rational number; if it cannot, then it is irrational.

STEP: <no title>
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

A fraction with a denominator equal to zero is neither rational nor irrational: it is "undefined," which means that it is not equal to anything.

The correct answer is neither.

Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

STEP: <no title>

If you work out the value of π7π7 with your calculator, you will find that it is quite a long decimal number. In fact, when you write an irrational number as a decimal, it will never terminate (end) and it will never repeat.

The correct answer is irrational.

Evaluating trigonometric expressions

Evaluate the following trigonometric expression without using a calculator:

tan30°×cos60°tan⁡30°×cos⁡60°
Answer:
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

Both of the angles given in the expression are special angles. Start by evaluating each of the trigonometric ratios of these special angles. Then reduce the resulting expression.

STEP: Evaluate each of the trigonometric ratios
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 2 points left]

The question asks us to evaluate this expression:

tan30°×cos60°tan⁡30°×cos⁡60°

One way to find the answer would be to type this into a calculator. But we have been told not to use one!

We need to realise here that the angles in the expresseion are both special angles. This means that we can determine the values of the trigonometric ratios exactly.

Evaluating each of the factors, we know that

tan30°=1√3cos60°=12tan⁡30°=13cos⁡60°=12

Substituting these values into the original expression, we get

tan30°×cos60°=1√3×12tan⁡30°×cos⁡60°=13×12
NOTE: You need to know the trigonometric ratios of the special angles for tests and exams. If you can't remember all of the ratios, start by drawing the special triangles. Then evaluate the ratio using the pictures.
STEP: Simplify the substituted expression
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

Now that we have the values of each of the factors in the expression, we can simplify to get the final answer:

tan30°×cos60°=1√3×12=12√3tan⁡30°×cos⁡60°=13×12=123

So the correct answer is:

tan30°×cos60°=12√3tan⁡30°×cos⁡60°=123
